<section xml:id="section-week8-activity">
  <title>Week 8 Activity</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-calculating-determinants">
    <title>Calculating Determinants</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the determinant of this matrix. Show the steps in
          the cofactor expansion.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix} 
              4 \amp 0 \amp -8 \\
              -1 \amp -2 \amp 3 \\
              5 \amp 0 \amp 0 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We cofactor expansion along the second column to take
          advantage of the zeros in that column. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \left| \begin{matrix} 
                4 \amp 0 \amp -8 \\
                -1 \amp -2 \amp 3 \\
                5 \amp 0 \amp 0 
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 
              (-1)(0) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp 3 \\ 
                5 \amp 0 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (1)(-2) \left| \begin{matrix}
                4 \amp -8 \\
                5 \amp 0 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (-1)(0) \left| \begin{matrix}
                4 \amp -8 \\
                -1 \amp 3 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The terms multiplied by zero are obviously zero. For the
          middle term, we use the formula for a <m>2 \times 2</m>
          determinant. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 0 + 2 \left[ (4)(0) - (5)(-8) \right] + 0 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp =  2 (40) = 80 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the determinant of this matrix. Show the steps in
          the cofactor expansion.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix} 
              0 \amp =2 \amp -2 \\
              1 \amp -6 \amp 1 \\
              -3 \amp 0 \amp 1 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We cofactor expansion along the first row
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \left| \begin{matrix} 
                0 \amp =2 \amp -2 \\
                1 \amp -6 \amp 1 \\
                -3 \amp 0 \amp 1 
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 
              (1)(0) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -6 \amp 1 \\
                0 \amp 1 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (-1)(-2) \left| \begin{matrix}
                1 \amp 1 \\
                -3 \amp 1 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (1)(-2) \left| \begin{matrix}
                 1 \amp -6 \\
                 -3 \amp 0
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The term multiplied by zero goes away. For the other two
          terms, we use the formula for <m>2 \times 2</m>
          determinants. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 0 + 2 \left[ (1)(1) - (1)(-3) \right] + 
              (-2) \left[ (1)(0) - (3)(-6) \right] 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 0 + 8 - 36 = -28
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the determinant of this matrix. Show the steps in
          the cofactor expansion.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix} 
              6 \amp -1 \amp 3 \\
              -4 \amp -2 \amp 0 \\
              -2 \amp -5 \amp 3 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We cofactor expansion along the third column, to take
          advantage of the zero term. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \left| \begin{matrix} 
                6 \amp -1 \amp 3 \\
                -4 \amp -2 \amp 0 \amp 
                -2 \amp -5 \amp 3 
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 
              (1)(3) (\left| \begin{matrix}
                -4 \amp -2 \\
                -2 \amp -5 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (-1)(0) \left| \begin{matrix}
                6 \amp -1 \\
                -2 \amp -5 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (1)(3) \left| \begin{matrix}
                6 \amp -1 \\
                -4 \amp -2 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The term multiplied by zero goes away. For the other two
          terms, we use the formula for the determinant of a <m>2
          \times 2</m> matrix. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp = (3) \left[ (-4)(-5) - (-2)(-2) \right] + 0 +
              (3) \left[ (6)(-2) - (-1)(-4) \right] 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 48 - 24 = 24 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the determinant of this matrix. Show the steps in
          the cofactor expansion.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix} 
              6 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 3 \\
              0 \amp 4 \amp 8 \amp 2 \\
              0 \amp 0 \amp -3 \amp 9 \\
              0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -7 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This is a upper triangular matrices. We know for any
          diagonal or triangular matrix, the determinant is just the
          product of the diagonal entires. 
          <me>
            \left| \begin{matrix} 
              6 \amp 2 \amp -1 \amp 3 \\
              0 \amp 4 \amp 8 \amp 2 \\
              0 \amp 0 \amp -3 \amp 9 \\
              0 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp -7 
            \end{matrix} \right|  = (6)(4)(-3)(-7) = 504
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the determinant of this matrix. Show the steps in
          the cofactor expansion.
          <me>
            \left( \begin{matrix} 
              4 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp 6 \\
              0 \amp -3 \amp 3 \amp -2 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
              -2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 
            \end{matrix} \right) 
          </me>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          We cofactor expansion along the first column to take
          advantage of the zero terms. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \left| \begin{matrix} 
              4 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp 6 \\
              0 \amp -3 \amp 3 \amp -2 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
              -2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 
              (1)(4) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -3 \amp 3 \amp -2 \\
                1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
                0 \amp 0 \amp 3 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (-1)(0) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp -1 \amp 6 \\
                1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
                0 \amp 0 \amp 3
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp + (1)(0) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp -1 \amp 6 \\
                -3 \amp 3 \amp -2 \\
                0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (-1)(-2) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp -1 \amp 6 \\
                -3 \amp 3 \amp -2 \\
                1 \amp 1 \amp -2 
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          The two terms multiplied by zero go away. We have two
          remaining <m>3 \times 3</m> determinants. We'll do these
          seperately and then put their determinant values back into
          the original equation. Here is the first one; we do cofactor
          expansion along the third row. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \left| \begin{matrix} 
                -3 \amp 3 \amp -2 \\
                1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
                0 \amp 0 \amp 3 
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 
              (1)(0) \left| \begin{matrix}
                3 \amp -2 \\
                1 \amp -2 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (-1)(0)  \left| \begin{matrix}
                -3 \amp -2 \\
                1 \amp -2 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (1)(3) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -3 \amp 3 \\
                1 \amp 1 
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 0 + 0 + 3 \left[ (-3)(1) - (3)(1) \right] 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = -18 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Here is the seoncd one; we do cofactor expansion along the
          first row. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \left| \begin{matrix} 
                -1 \amp -1 \amp 6 \\
                -3 \amp 3 \amp -2 
                1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 
              (1)(-1) \left| \begin{matrix}
                3 \amp -2 \\
                1 \amp -2 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (-1)(-1) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -3 \amp -2 \\
                1 \amp -2 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (1)(6) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -3 \amp 3 \\
                1 \amp 1
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = (-1) \left[ (3)(-2) - (1)(-2) \right] 
              + (1) \left[ (-3)(-2) - (1)(-2) \right] 
              + (6) \left[ (-3)(1) - (1)(3) \right] 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 4 + 8 - 36 = -24 
            </mrow>
          </md>
          Now we put these back into the full expression.
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \amp \left| \begin{matrix} 
              4 \amp -1 \amp -1 \amp 6 \\
              0 \amp -3 \amp 3 \amp -2 \\
              0 \amp 1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
              -2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \amp 3 
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 
              (1)(4) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -3 \amp 3 \amp -2 \\
                1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
                0 \amp 0 \amp 3 
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (-1)(0) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp -1 \amp 6 \\
                1 \amp 1 \amp -2 \\
                0 \amp 0 \amp 3
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp + (1)(0) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp -1 \amp 6 \\
                -3 \amp 3 \amp -2 \\
                0 \amp 0 \amp 3 \\
              \end{matrix} \right| + 
              (-1)(-2) \left| \begin{matrix}
                -1 \amp -1 \amp 6 \\
                -3 \amp 3 \amp -2 \\ 
                1 \amp 1 \amp -2 
              \end{matrix} \right| 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = 4 (-18) + 0 + 0 + 2(-24) = -120
            </mrow> 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
